This article is a Presidential Proclamation issued by Barack Obama in 2010 to commemorate Workers Memorial Day. The proclamation highlights the importance of workplace safety and the need to honor and remember those who have died, been injured, or become sick on the job. It mentions recent workplace tragedies, such as the explosion at the Upper Big Branch Mine in West Virginia and a refinery explosion in Washington State. The proclamation emphasizes the legal right to a safe workplace and calls for concerted action from government, businesses, unions, and individuals to provide safer work environments. It concludes by designating April 28, 2010, as Workers Memorial Day and calling upon all Americans to participate in ceremonies and activities in memory of those who have been killed due to unsafe working conditions.